# Deterministic line endings, independent of each contributor's
# core.autocrlf. Without this, a Windows checkout (autocrlf=true) rewrites
# install.sh to CRLF, which then fails under bash (`install.sh: set: Illegal
# option -`); normalizing here keeps the repo and every checkout consistent.

# Default: treat everything as text, store it as LF in the repo, and check it
# out as LF on every platform. POSIX shell scripts, the seed.sh shell
# integration, seedling.conf (parsed line-by-line by bash), Python, and docs
# all require LF.
* text=auto eol=lf

# The Windows entry points are sh/batch polyglots. cmd.exe needs CRLF to read
# them as batch, and their line-1 `:; exec sh ...installers/install.sh`
# comment is deliberately crafted so the trailing CR falls inside the comment
# -- so `sh ./install.cmd` on macOS/Linux still hands off cleanly (verified:
# a CRLF install.cmd execs the LF install.sh under dash with no error). Keep
# them CRLF on every checkout.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
